## Quick Win: The -ν Rule

<insight name="nu-rule" highlight="true">
<title>When uncertain, use the -ν form</title>
<explanation>
You'll never be wrong if you keep the final -ν on τον/την/στον/στην.
Native speakers sometimes drop it, but keeping it is never wrong.
</explanation>
<example>τον φίλο or τη φίλη - both correct!</example>
</insight>

---

## The -ν Rule (Movable Nu) - Detailed

<section name="movable-nu">
<title>Fine-tuning: when to keep or drop final -ν on articles</title>

<rule>
Keep the -ν before vowels and certain consonants (κ, π, τ, γκ, μπ, ντ, ξ, ψ).
Drop the -ν before other consonants.
</rule>

### Keep the -ν
- τον άνθρωπο (before vowel α)
- την πόρτα (before π)
- στον κήπο (before κ)

### Drop the -ν
- τη μητέρα (before μ)
- τη θάλασσα (before θ)
- στο σπίτι (neuter - no ν anyway)

</section>

